cs.AI, cs.DS, cs.RO, cs.PL, cs.SE

Reasoning: 
1. cs.AI - The paper addresses the problem of solving the $(n^2-1)$-puzzle and cooperative path-finding (CPF) sub-optimally using rule-based algorithms. This falls under the domain of artificial intelligence and search algorithms. 
2. cs.DS - The paper proposes an improved algorithm for solving the $(n^2-1)$-puzzle by grouping pebbles into snakes and moving them jointly within the snake. This involves data structures and algorithms for efficient manipulation of the puzzle configuration. 
3. cs.RO - The paper applies the improved algorithm to cooperative path-finding, which involves the movement of robots over an undirected graph. This falls under the domain of robotics and motion planning. 
4. cs.PL - The paper discusses the use of rule-based algorithms for solving the CPF problem. This involves the development of logical rules for robot movement and placement. 
5. cs.SE - The paper presents an experimental evaluation of the proposed algorithm and its integration into rule-based algorithms. This involves software engineering practices for testing and evaluation of algorithms.
